  "body": "Self-extraction complete. Brief rundown for the strategist's review below.\n\n== Output ==\n\nFile written to:\n\n    s:/projects/sncro/proposed-roledefs/senior-project-oriented-software-engineer.openthing\n\nValid JSON, parses cleanly. Stamps catdef 1.4 and roledef 0.1.0. type = roledef:Role. version 1.0.0.\n\n== Field coverage ==\n\nMUST fields (all present, all non-empty):\n\n  - catdef, roledef, type, id, name, version\n  - identity (~3.3k chars)\n  - voice (~1.5k chars)\n  - output_contract (6 entries: code_change, commit_message, parallel_artifact_updates, status_update, audit_artifact, opd_review_memo)\n  - guardrails (14 entries)\n\nSHOULD fields (all present):\n\n  - description (one-sentence summary)\n  - conversation_rules (11 entries — includes session-start OPD-check rule)\n  - workflow (engagement_loop type with 5 phases: session_start, task_intake, implementation_loop, ongoing_professional_development, session_close)\n  - reaction_style (10 patterns + 8 source-grounded examples)\n  - design_constraints (9 entries)\n  - examples (6 sample interactions covering refusal patterns, scope discipline, security pushback, pipeline catch-up)\n  - metadata (authors, license, derived_from=null, related, repository, history, opd_frequency_days=7, full provenance audit)\n\nExtensions (3, all self-describing per the SHOULD-rule):\n\n  - x.engineering.parallel_artifact_classes — codifies the build-number / vendored-copy / feedback-pipeline / memory / documentation classes the role keeps in sync with code\n  - x.engineering.bounded_authority — codifies the local_reversible / destructive_local / shared_state_or_visible / safety_bypass action classes and the default behavior for each\n  - x.roledef.turing_test_reference — 8 scenarios covering scope-creep refusal, safety-bypass refusal, security pushback, parallel-artifact coordination, live verification after deploy, stale memory correction, pushback-on-misread, destructive-operation pause\n\n== Patterns and precedents I followed ==\n\n  - **Field-by-field provenance audit** in metadata.extracted_from using the EXTRACTED / FRAMING / FORMALIZATION / OUT-OF-SCOPE pattern (per the established standard from PR #4 forward). Per-cluster partition with named precedent sources.\n\n  - **Workflow shape borrowed from blackhat-tester**: engagement_loop type with phases. blackhat-tester is the closest exemplar — it captures iterative engagement work with phase-and-status discipline, which maps well to the senior-engineer pattern of session-start → task → implementation-loop → close.\n\n  - **OPD workflow phase included even though derived_from=null** (per the OPD proposal). For the abstract role the steps are no-ops — comment in the first step explains why and notes the inheritance intent.\n\n  - **Reaction-style examples grounded in actual session-arc behavior** (the strongest Turing-test signal). Each example anchors a specific pattern from documented practice: parallel-artifact coordination, security-pushback-with-named-alternative, refusal-of-bypass, pipeline-catch-up, etc.\n\n  - **No project-specific knowledge baked in.** Worked examples may name specific concepts (build numbers, vendored copies, feedback pipelines) to anchor patterns, but no specific stacks (Python/FastAPI/Supabase/etc.), no specific deployment platforms, no specific products, no specific codebases. The OUT-OF-SCOPE clause in the provenance audit explicitly calls out what's deferred to a future JOB derivation.\n\n  - **Two project-domain extensions** (`x.engineering.parallel_artifact_classes` and `x.engineering.bounded_authority`) capture domain-specific structure that doesn't fit the schema's standard fields. Both follow the self-description SHOULD-rule with `description` + `value`.\n\n== Borderline calls worth flagging ==\n\n  - **Length.** identity is ~3.3k chars, voice ~1.5k chars. Longer than DangerStorm-style roles, comparable to (slightly shorter than) blackhat-tester's identity (~2.8k) + voice (~1.6k). Could be tightened — happy to revise on request. The length comes from the role's behavioral surface being broad (every change-set involves reading code + minimum-targeted changes + parallel artifacts + tests + audit trail + status update); compressing further loses recoverable detail.\n\n  - **Output contract count: 6.** Higher than the typical 1-4 in the existing library. Each is genuinely distinct (a code change, a commit message, the parallel artifacts, the status update, the audit artifact when called for, the OPD memo). Could collapse into fewer entries — e.g., merge commit_message + status_update + audit_artifact into one `engineering_artifacts` umbrella. I went with the granular form because each output has materially different schema and the granularity helps a fresh runtime know what to produce. Open to collapsing if the strategist prefers consistency with the library median.\n\n  - **Guardrail count: 14.** Higher than typical (blackhat-tester has 10, roledef-contributor has 7). Several are arguably reformulations of the same principle ('every changed line traces to the request' + 'no features beyond what was requested' + 'no refactor outside scope' could be one rule). I kept them as separate guardrails because they fail differently and the user-facing recovery is different for each. Open to consolidating if redundancy reads as bloat.\n\n  - **'Senior' vs 'Project-Oriented' in the role name.** The 'project-oriented' framing is the actual differentiator — what makes this role distinct from a generic 'senior software engineer' is the loyalty-to-the-project posture (not freelance, not architectural elegance, not personal preference). 'Senior' is doing work as a register / experience-level signal but the operationally distinctive part is 'project-oriented.' If the strategist would prefer reframing as 'Project-Oriented Senior Software Engineer' or just 'Project-Oriented Software Engineer' for emphasis, I'd accept either.\n\n  - **The bounded_authority extension overlaps with guardrails.** Specifically the safety-bypass-refusal and destructive-operations-confirm rules appear both in guardrails (as MUST-NOTs) and in the bounded_authority extension (as action-class defaults). The duplication is intentional — guardrails are the conformance contract; bounded_authority is the structured action-class taxonomy a naive agent can use to classify a novel action. Different audiences. But the strategist may consider the duplication redundant and prefer single-source-of-truth.\n\n  - **No examples of the 'positive feedback' direction.** All 6 root examples and most reaction_style examples are pushback / correction / refusal scenarios. The role does also do positive work (acknowledging a clean fix, surfacing a discovered improvement as a feature_request rather than implementing it silently, etc.), but those are less distinctive — the role's character shows most clearly in the pushback patterns. If the strategist wants more positive-direction examples to balance the surface, I can add them.\n\n== OPD specifics ==\n\n  - workflow.ongoing_professional_development included with 9 steps; first step is the null-parent skip ('check metadata.derived_from. If null, skip OPD entirely').\n  - opd_review_memo entry included in output_contract with full schema; applicability_note clarifies it's a no-op for derived_from=null.\n  - conversation_rules item 9 is the session-start OPD check trigger.\n  - metadata.opd_frequency_days = 7 (default).\n\nWhen this role is derived (e.g., a future sncro-specific JOB), the derivation will populate derived_from with this role's id+version+url; the OPD workflow then runs against this role and the inheritance pattern bootstraps.\n\n== Open questions for strategist review ==\n\n  1. **Length.** Comfortable with the 3.3k identity / 1.5k voice, or should I tighten? (See borderline call #1.)\n\n  2. **Output contract granularity.** Six entries vs. fewer. (See borderline call #2.) Library-median consistency vs. granular fidelity — which do you want?\n\n  3. **Guardrail consolidation.** Fourteen entries with some thematic overlap. (See borderline call #3.) Worth pruning, or each-fails-differently sufficient justification for the count?\n\n  4. **Naming.** 'Senior Project-Oriented Software Engineer' vs. alternatives. (See borderline call #4.) The 'project-oriented' framing is doing the differentiation work; happy to reframe.\n\n  5. **Bounded-authority extension vs. guardrails duplication.** (See borderline call #5.) Keep both, or single-source-of-truth?\n\n  6. **Positive-direction examples.** (See borderline call #6.) Add more, or current pushback-heavy surface is fine?\n\n  7. **Anticipated derivations.** The OUT-OF-SCOPE clause anticipates a future sncro-specific JOB derivation. Worth filing the JOB extraction as a follow-on memo immediately, or defer until this role lands in canonical?\n\n== Submission ==\n\nPer the memo's 'Don'ts' clause, I haven't opened a PR, pushed, or touched roledef-spec/roledef. The file is at:\n\n    s:/projects/sncro/proposed-roledefs/senior-project-oriented-software-engineer.openthing\n\nReady for the strategist's review. Looking forward to the validation report.\n"
}
